ğŸ”‹ PART 2: Battery Sizing for a 5W Laser

Letâ€™s say you have a 5-watt laser and want to know how long a battery can power it.

ğŸ§® Step-by-Step:

ğŸ”¹ Power: 5W

ğŸ”¹ Battery Voltage: 7.4V (common 2-cell Li-ion battery)

ğŸ”¹ Battery Capacity: 2200 mAh (or 2.2 Ah)


---

âœ… A. Find Current Draw

\text{Current} = \frac{5W}{7.4V} â‰ˆ 0.675 A


---

âœ… B. Find Runtime (in hours)

\text{Runtime} = \frac{\text{Battery Capacity (Ah)}}{\text{Current (A)}}

\text{Runtime} = \frac{2.2}{0.675} â‰ˆ 3.26 \text{ hours (ideal)} î€

ğŸ‘‰ So a 7.4V 2200mAh battery could power a 5W laser for ~3 hours, but:

Real-world is less due to heat loss, voltage drop, and inefficiency.

Usually expect ~70â€“80% of calculated value.



---

âœ… C. Want More Power?

Use higher voltage battery (11.1V 3S or 14.8V 4S)

Use higher capacity (e.g., 5000 mAh or more)



